{
  "doc_id": "14471",
  "text": "STK11 is also associated with energy metabolism, either alone or by interacting with AMPK, making it a potential bridge protein involved in the regulation of energy metabolism [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Among the other bridge proteins involved in energy metabolism are PPARGC1A, GSK3B, PPARA, peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARG), solute carrier family 2 (facilitated glucose transporter) member 4 (SLC2A4, also known as GLUT4), glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase (GAPDH), and lactate dehydrogenase A (LDHA), all important regulators of or enzymes involved in energy metabolism. Thus, their molecular functions may explain the activities of BAs that increase energy expenditure [CITATION_3] . Assessments of the molecular functions of bridge proteins may provide novel insights on their as yet unidentified roles in BA homeostasis.",
